cturing and away from high levels of CO2 emissions was predictably reaffirmed at the conference. It was left to the Indian representative, Mr. Mahesh Prasad, to argue against the manifestly untenable expectation that the Third World countries would willingly abandon their developmental objectives by forswearing expansion of thermal power generation or the inevitably energy intensive pattern of industrialisation. Although the developing countries find themselves in a hapless predicament in not being able to commit themselves to time bound environmental action plans such as having the use of chlorofluorcarbons (CFCs) by the end of the century as prescribed by the Montreal Protocol of September 1987 and the proposal for graduated mitigation of carbon dioxide emissions brought up at the Noordwijk conference there is fortunately no prospect of global warming being treated as a totally extraneous issue by these countries. Nor is there any doubt that the consequences of the green house effect for low lying countries such as Egypt, Maldives and Vanuatu would be so fearsome as to call for determined global preventive action.
