ARE THE FOREBONDINGS about the impending global warming really producing the inteded policy responses from the governments of the various countries ? \'Not so\' would be the answer, judging from the fate of the recent global conference, sponsored by the Netherelands Government at Noordwijk. Here was a gathering of representatives - climatologists and ministers of environment - of 60 countries including the U.S, Britian, the Soviet Union, Japan and India. On the agenda before the conference were three crucial issues relating to the stemming of the so-called excesses of the greenhouse effect or the global build up of carbon dioxide. First there was the question of the industrial countries agreeing upon freezing carbon dioxide emissions at current levels by 2000 A.D and achieving 20 percent cuts by 2005 A.D first mooted at the Toronto World Conference of June 1988. Second, there was the proposal to concert a world-wide afforestation programme covering 12 million hectares per year as a method of combating decreased carbon fixation caused by the unstoppable deforestation all over the third world. Third, the conference also sought to obtain a mandate for a perpraratory draft for a global convention on climate. None of these aims, in fact, has materialised. The industrial countries, without exception, have turned down the proposition that they should adopt a time bound containment of CO2 emissions through appropriate changes in the industrial system and in the energy mix underpinning it. Although the resistance to any such commitment by countries such as the US and Britain is not difficult to understand in view of the paucity of empirical information on what the costs of industrial restructuring would be, there can hardly be any doubt that these countries are yet to overcome their allergic altitude to the very concept of moving away from the dominant fossil fuel energy development. Japan\'s well-known stance of having moved resolutely ahead on the path of industrial restructuring and away from high levels of CO2 emissions was predictably reaffirmed at the conference. It was left to the Indian representative, Mr. Mahesh Prasad, to argue against the manifestly untenable expectation that the Third World countries would willingly abandon their developmental objectives by forswearing expansion of thermal power generation or the inevitably energy intensive pattern of industrialisation. Although the developing countries find themselves in a hapless predicament in not being able to commit themselves to time bound environmental action plans such as having the use of chlorofluorcarbons (CFCs) by the end of the century as prescribed by the Montreal Protocol of September 1987 and the proposal for graduated mitigation of carbon dioxide emissions brought up at the Noordwijk conference there is fortunately no prospect of global warming being treated as a totally extraneous issue by these countries. Nor is there any doubt that the consequences of the green house effect for low lying countries such as Egypt, Maldives and Vanuatu would be so fearsome as to call for determined global preventive action.

